struct foo&lt;unsigned __int64,-1&gt;  // &lt;===== bug revealed?
max: 18446744073709551615
</code></pre>
<p>When struct <code>foo</code> is instantiated with <code>unsigned long long</code>, the name reported by <code>std::type_info::name()</code> treats template parameter <code>Max</code> as though it were signed.</p>
<p>With type <code>unsigned int</code>, it does not make that mistake.</p>
<p>I have tested all built-in unsigned integer types. Type <code>unsigned long long</code> is the only one that reports <code>-1</code>. All the others correctly report the unsigned value. To me, this shows Microsoft's intent to report the correct unsigned value, and not <code>-1</code>. That is why I suspect the compiler is not doing what Microsoft intends.</p>
<p>Is this a bug? If so, is it a known bug?</p>
