<p>I've found a difference between the outputs of very basic programs using the FFTW library in C++ and the pyFFTW library in Python.</p>
<p>The following is a minimal reproducable example.</p>
<p>With pyFFTW version <code>0.15.0</code>:</p>
<pre><code>import numpy as np
import pyfftw

K = pyfftw.empty_aligned(4, dtype='complex128')
X = pyfftw.empty_aligned(4, dtype='complex128')
ifftDoer = pyfftw.FFTW(K, X, direction='FFTW_BACKWARD')

K[:] = np.array([1, 2, 3, 4])

ifftDoer()

print(X)

&gt; OUTPUT: [ 2.5+0.j  -0.5-0.5j -0.5+0.j  -0.5+0.5j]
</code></pre>
<p>With FFTW version <code>3.3.8</code>:</p>
<pre><code>int main() {

    int N = 4;

    fftw_complex *in, *out;
    fftw_plan p;
    in = (fftw_complex*) fftw_malloc(sizeof(fftw_complex) * N);
    out = (fftw_complex*) fftw_malloc(sizeof(fftw_complex) * N);
    p = fftw_plan_dft_1d(N, in, out, FFTW_BACKWARD, FFTW_ESTIMATE);

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; 4; i++) {
        in[i][0] = i+1;
        in[i][1] = 0;
    }

    fftw_execute(p);
    printFFTWComplexArr(out, N);
    fftw_destroy_plan(p);
}

&gt; OUTPUT: (10, 0), (-2, -2), (-2, 0), (-2, 2),
</code></pre>
